An '''amanuensis''' (derived from a [[Latin]] expression which may be literally translated as "manual labourer") is a person who writes down the words of another. The term is sometimes used interchangably with [[secretary]], but is also used in a more specific sense in some [[academic]] contexts, for instance when an [[injury|injured]] or [[disability|disabled]] person is helped by an amanuensis at a written [[examination]]. 

Before the advent of the [[printing press]], an amanuensis was a person, usually but not exclusively a [[monk]], who functioned as a [[scribe]]. 

In [[Norway]] and [[Denmark]], ''amanuensis'' is an [[academic rank]] corresponing to that of [[assistant professor]] in the [[United States]]. ''Førsteamanuensis'' ([[Norwegian language|Norwegian]] and [[Danish language|Danish]] for "first amanuensis") is the equivalent of [[associate professor]].

